In the world of finance and investments, you may hear the terms \"sell side\" and \"buy side\". What do they mean? Sell Side Who They Are: Primarily investment banks, broker-dealers, and other firms that facilitate buying and selling of securities. What They Do: Provide advisory, underwriting, and brokerage services. They often generate research reports, help companies raise capital through IPOs, and assist with mergers & acquisitions. Revenue Model: Typically earned through fees and commissions on trades. Buy Side Who They Are: Asset managers, hedge funds, mutual funds, pension funds, and private equity firms that invest capital on behalf of clients or the firm itself. What They Do: Focus on managing investments and portfolios. Their goal is to generate returns for their investors or stakeholders. Revenue Model: Often based on management and performance fees, reflecting how effectively they grow investments. Key Distinctions: Perspective ‚Äì Sell side advises and executes transactions, while buy side allocates capital to generate returns. Clients ‚Äì Sell side primarily works for corporate or institutional clients needing capital or advisory services; buy side serves investors (institutional or individual) seeking growth or income.
